Perhaps nowhere is California’s mental health crisis more evident than in its criminal justice system.
After decades of failure to create and fund policies that effectively help people with serious mental illnesses, many now say the jails and prisons have become the state’s default mental institutions.
Close to a third of California’s inmates have a documented serious mental illness, according to the California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation.
Often this leaves people who need mental health treatment stuck in county jails.
Judge Stephen Manley started one of the nation’s first mental health courts in Santa Clara County more than 20 years ago.